text: hi everyone Tiffany bucktanno here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for review of the new self-titled
Royal Blood album this is the debut
full-length album of Brighton
alternative rock and hard rock band
Royal Blood which features the drum and
bass guitar stylings of Ben Thatcher and
Michael Kerr you might already know the
band through such singles as come on
over and figure it out in little monster
or out of the black if you take a listen
to Royal blood's music you're going to
hear a lot of drum beats that feel like
they're coming from the old school of
classic rock or alternative rock in the
90s the recording of the drums sounds
very modern it's very Punchy and then on
top of these drums are many heavy
buzzing slightly Sinister at times bass
riffs these bass riffs are very thick
they're very distorted sometimes it
sounds like we're hearing a bit of a
bass over dub thing like we're getting a
distorted bass signal and then maybe a
clean signal to play underneath and
sound very clean very resonant and
they're kind of mixed together basically
the bass guitar being the only electric
guitar type instrument in the mix is
mimicking the sound of a regular guitar
imagine if you will the instrumental
stylings of a band like Death from Above
1979 mixed with the songwriting style of
like Queens of the Stone Age really cool
idea in theory however I've been having
a really difficult time getting into one
of this album's lead tracks out of the
black one of the band's biggest songs a
track that given its popularity you
would think this is the easiest song to
get into or the key song to enjoy even
if you don't really enjoy the rest of
the record but personally I'm just
having a hard time seeing the hype
behind this track especially given it's
incredibly stiff intro riff and drum
syncopation plus a singing voice I
couldn't pick out of a lineup to save my
life and some verses that are pretty
throwaway lyrically and melodically the
verses on this track only feel like a
very underwhelming placeholder it's the
part that isn't really grabbing your
attention so that when the chorus comes
around it feels like an explosion like
whoa I've just been grabbed it kind of
feels like the song has just gotten
exciting when it's only gone from boring
to mildly interesting and this formula
is essentially repeated on song after
song after song on tracks like come on
over where we get another bass line that
feels like it could have come straight
from a Death from Above 1979 song with
some wailing bass riffs that feel a
little hendrix-esque and these very
obvious similarities only become greater
on tracks like bloodhands where the
singing is like a dead ringer for a
vocal that you would find on a 2000s
Arab White Stripes album it literally
sounds like a song Jack White has
written and then 10 ton skeleton this
track should have just been on the new
DFA 1979 record I don't mind a bit of
rock revivalism but it feels like Royal
Blood at times is writing songs
completely off of the back of the 2000s
Rock revivalism the stripes the keys the
kills and Royal Blood come through with
significantly less grit virtuosity
songwriting ability personality and Edge
than these bands it's like listening to
a really watered-down copy of a Xerox to
me all this record really has are some
passable performances some overly simple
songs and some heavy production and even
these likable things aren't even used in
the best of taste like on the track
little monsters
is this an Audioslave album where did
this riff come from the White Stripes
may have certainly had their commercial
moments on records like get behind me
Satan or on elephant but I have never
heard a band more desperate to appeal to
the alternative rock radio Market than
Royal Blood on this song the whole Duo
thing is cool some of my favorite acts
in rock music happen to be Duos but
without some significant over dubbing
and some really good songwriting there's
not much to the tracks Royal Blood
delivers on this album because this
album is so lacking in anything original
exciting or gutsy that it completely
negates the very Baseline positive
things this record has going on for it
I'm feeling a strong four to a light
five on this thing transition if you've
given this record a listen what did you
think of it did you love it did you hate
